  "buggy_files": ["sound/pci/hda/hda_intel.c"],
  "buggy_functions": ["azx_rirb_get_response", "azx_init_chip", "azx_resume", "azx_runtime_resume"],
  "confidence": 0.85,
  "reasoning": "The bug occurs because HDA Intel driver state variables used for error recovery/fallback modes are not being reset during system resume. Specifically: (1) chip->polling_mode is set to 1 when a codec response timeout occurs, but is never reset back to 0 during resume, causing the driver to remain in polling mode after wakeup; (2) chip->poll_count is incremented on timeouts but never reset during resume; (3) chip->single_cmd is set to 1 as a fallback when communication errors occur, but is not reset during resume, preventing proper reinitialization of the CORB/RIRB command interface on the resumed hardware. The suspension calls azx_stop_chip() which sets chip->initialized=0, and resume calls azx_init_chip(chip, 1) which re-initializes hardware, but this flow does not reset the fallback mode state variables (polling_mode, poll_count, single_cmd). After multiple suspend/resume cycles where timeouts occur, these variables accumulate in fallback mode states, causing the sound card to operate with degraded communication modes (single_cmd, polling) that produce choppy audio after resume. The fix requires resetting chip->polling_mode and chip->poll_count to their initial values (0) during azx_init_chip when full_reset=1, and ensuring the CORB/RIRB command I/O is properly reinitialized even if chip->single_cmd was set to 1 by error recovery."
}

